[2] Taiwan - vectors, cases
Date: 29 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Taipei Times, 26 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2006/07/26/2003320438>

Dengue fever may pose an increasing threat to the south of the
country, the Center for Disease Control said yesterday [25 Jul 2006].
After Tropical Storm Bilis struck, the density of mosquitoes
transmitting the illness rose substantially, the center said at a
press conference. Center Deputy Director Lin Ting said there have
been 59 cases of dengue fever this year [2006], of which 17 were
contracted within the country. 15 of these 17 cases were reported in
Cianjhen and Cianjin Districts in Kaohsiung City this summer. The
neighborhoods where the Kaohsiung cases were reported are close to
one another, Lin said. The other 42 cases were contracted abroad,
with most cases coming from Viet Nam, Indonesia, Thailand and the
Philippines, the center said. Senior citizens in northern Taiwan
should also beware of mosquito bites, because the elderly are more
vulnerable to Japanese encephalitis, the center said.
[Byline Flora Wang]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
