[7] Brazil - Recife
Date: 18 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-PORT <Promed-Port@promedmail.org>
Source: Noticias 360 graus, 18 Jul 2006 [Trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://pe360graus.globo.com>

The increase in the number of cases in Recife this year [2006] is
worrisome. According to the State Secretary of Health (SES), there
has been a 151 per cent increase in the number of registered cases of
this disease from January to July of this year [2006] compared to the
same period in 2005. According to the Secretariat, 95 per cent of the
neighborhoods of the capital are considered as at high or very high
risk of transmission.
"We have 2 questions that explain this increase: intermittent
availability of water, which obligates people to store water, and
also an increase in use of discarded [water] recipients, which serve
as breeding places for mosquitoes," said Sinara Batista, Director of
the Environmental Health Program of Recife. She explained also that
the collaboration of the population is fundamental to effectively
combat the disease. Water storage containers and other recipients
used to keep water must be covered. An environmental health officer
will go from house-to-house several times each year [to correct] the
same situations.
This year [2006], 4 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever were confirmed,
and another 25 are under investigation.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
