[9] Brazil - Sao Paulo State
Date: 26 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EPTV Globo, 25 Jul 2006 [Trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
<http://eptv.globo.com/noticias/noticias_interna.asp?145209>

Dengue mosquito infestation grew 35 percent in Ribeirao Preto [Sao
Paulo State]. The city has already reported 2182 cases of this
disease this year [2006]
-----------------------------------------------
The infestation index of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, the dengue
vector, increased by 35 percent in Ribeirao Preto compared with the
same period last year [2005]. In 2005, the index was 1.7 per cent,
and now it has reached 2.3 per cent according to the prefecture.
The city has been affected by an epidemic of dengue since October
2005 and has already confirmed 2182 cases.
All parts of the city have been positive for foci of the disease. In
the neighborhoods Jardim California and Jardim Canada, undergrowth
and open sewers are of concern. The mosquitoes are all over the
place. The prefecture affirmed that it is taking measures and that by
the end of 2008, the city sewage will be treated.
Prefectural technicians said that the residents should use insect
repellent and not use insecticides.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Water containers in and around houses are more likely to be the
significant sites of _Aedes aegypti_ breeding than are open sewers. - Mod.TY]
[It is unclear what "infestation" index was used in the present
study, as there are several larval indices that have commonly been
used to compare population size of _Aedes aegypti_ in different areas
and at different times. The most commonly used larval indices are:
1) House or Premise Index. The percentage of houses, including
examinations of surrounding compounds, that have larvae of _Ae.
aegypti_ in at least some containers.
2) Container or Receptacle Index. The percentage of water-holding
containers that contain larvae of _Ae. aegypti_.
3) Breteau Index. The total number of containers with larvae of _Ae.
aegypti_ per 100 houses.
Another index is the egg index, which detects egg laying. This can be
monitored by using cheap and simple ovitraps that commonly consist of
a strip of absorbent material, e.g. hardboard or velour paper, placed
in a tin can or jar containing water. Female _Ae. aegypti_ deposit
their eggs on the wet strip. The percentage of such traps with eggs
of _Ae. aegypti_ can provide some measure of the relative population
size of the vector.
An excellent publication comparing the different methods of
evaluating infestation levels of _Ae. aegypti_ in northeastern Brazil
is by Morato, V.C.G. et al. (2005) Infestation of _Aedes aegypti_
estimated by oviposition traps in Brazil. Rev. Saude Publica, 39: 553-558.
Further information on larval indices can be found in ProMED archive
number 20060406.1032.
Although it is unclear what index was used in the present study in
Ribeirao Preto, an increase from 1.7 to 2.3 does not seem very large.
The use of indices to reflect population size of _Ae. aegypti_ and
then to relate this with virus transmission is fraught with
difficulties. - Mod.MS]
******
[10] Venezuela
Date: 28 Jul 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Epidemiological Alert, Epidemiological Week 28 [Trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.msds.gov.ve/msds/Boletines/Alertas/2006/Boletin28_2006.zip>

During the current epidemiological week [9-15 Jul 2006], 920 dengue
cases were diagnosed, of which 65 (7.1 per cent) were hemorrhagic,
with a dengue fever/DHF ratio of 13:1.
The cumulative [number of dengue cases] this year [2006] is 23 733,
of which 5.5 per cent were DHF (1296 cases), with a DF/DHF ratio of 17:1.
The cumulative mortality rate is 89.3 per 100 000 inhabitants. The
[dengue virus] serotypes circulating are 1, 2, 3, and 4. The
cumulative [number of dengue cases] for the current period have
increased by 34.4 per cent, compared to the cumulative number of
cases for the same dates last year [2005] (17 027 cases). During the
current year 2006, no dengue deaths have been reported.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
