[11] Cuba
Date: 21 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Cubanet [Trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.cubanet.org/CNews/y06/jul06/21a1.htm>

More than 600 dengue cases have been reported in the municipalities
of Cerro, Centro Habana [Central Havana] and Arroyo Naranjo,
according to various employees in the public health sector, who
request anonymity.
Also, there have been meetings with physicians and nurses at zone and
neighborhood levels, in which the authorities are informing people
about the situation and, at the same time, are carrying out tests [on
individuals] in the population who have presented or present symptoms
of the disease.
The Habana Vieja [Old Havana] municipality has begun clean-up of
places that are closed or abandoned with the goal of eliminating
possible foci of _Aedes aegypti_, the mosquito that transmits dengue.
The last time that the Cuban capital was faced with this situation
was in 2002, which resulted in an extensive clean-up campaign of the
city. On that occasion, one million cubic meters of accumulated
garbage and trash was collected from the streets and avenues of the
city of Havana.
[Byline Jose Antonio Fornaris]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is not an official report from the Cuban government. ProMED
requests information from the Cuban Ministry of Health concerning the
numbers of cases of dengue and of DHF, the dengue virus serotype or
serotypes being transmitted, and progress of the clean-up campaign. - Mod.TY]
